            "text": "To create a new nbdev project using a GitHub template, you can follow these steps:\n\n1.  **Install nbdev:**\n    *   Open a terminal or command prompt.\n    *   Run `pip install nbdev` or `conda install -c fastai nbdev`.\n\n2.  **Create a GitHub Repository:**\n    *   Go to GitHub and create a new, empty repository.\n    *   You can use the `nbdev_template` from fastai as a starting point. Alternatively, you can use the `nbdev_new` command to initialize a project from an existing GitHub repository.\n\n3.  **Initialize Your nbdev Project:**\n    *   Clone your newly created GitHub repository to your local machine.\n    *   Navigate into the repository's directory in your terminal.\n    *   Run `nbdev_new` to initialize your nbdev project. This command will infer project information from Git and GitHub and prompt you for any remaining details. It sets up files for package publishing, documentation with Quarto, and GitHub Actions for testing and deployment.\n\n4.  **Configure Your Project:**\n    *   Edit the `settings.ini` file (or `pyproject.toml` in newer versions) to configure your project's metadata, such as library name, description, author, and copyright. This is crucial for documentation hosting on GitHub Pages and for publishing your package to PyPI.\n\n5.  **Develop Your Project:**\n    *   Write your code in Jupyter notebooks within the `nbs` directory.\n    *   Use nbdev's features for documentation, testing, and code export.\n\n6.  **Build and Preview Documentation:**\n    *   Run `nbdev_prepare` to export code from notebooks, run tests, clean notebooks, and update your README.\n    *   You can preview your documentation locally before deploying it to GitHub Pages. This often involves running a Jekyll server, which may require installing Ruby and Jekyll. Commands like `make docs_serve` can be used for local previewing.\n\n7.  **Commit and Push to GitHub:**\n    *   Commit your changes to your local repository.\n    *   Push your changes to your GitHub repository.\n\n8.  **Enable GitHub Pages:**\n    *   In your GitHub repository's settings, navigate to \"Pages.\"\n    *   Set the source to build from the `/docs` folder of the master branch.\n    *   Once configured, GitHub Pages will host your documentation website.\n\nFor a more detailed walkthrough, you can refer to the nbdev tutorials available online."
